# The tr Command:
#----------------

-> The tr commnd can be used to translate or delete characters.

-> Most of the time tr command is used with other commands.

Example 1:
    
    # echo "Hello, World" | tr [a-z] [A-Z] //This prints "HELLO, WORLD". The tr command converts all lowercase letters to uppercase letters.

Example 2:

    Method 1:

        # cat sample_file.txt | tr [a-z] [A-Z]

        # cat sample_file.txt | tr [:lower:] [:upper:]

    Method 2:

        # tr [a-z] [A-Z] < sample_file.txt

Example 3:

    # echo "Hello, World" | tr -d  [a-z] //This prints only the capital letters. The -d options removes all lowercase letters.

Example 4:

    # echo <file-name> | tr -s "t" //This command checks the file and removes duplicate letters of 't' in the file. The -s stands for squeeze.

Example 5:

    # echo "Hello World 123" | tr -d [:alpha;] //This output only 123

Example 6:

    # echo "Hello_ World" | tr "_" "," //This command replaces the uderscore with a comma.
